In this case, the model writes

$$
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}
y_{j} = f(\psib, t_j) + \epsilon_j,
\end{split}
\end{equation}
$$ {#eq-nlm-one}

i.e. the subject's index $i$ is dropped and the only measurement variation is due to the measurement timing, with the least-squares estimate given by

$$
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}
\widehat{\psib}
=
\arg\min_{\psib}
\sum_{j=1}^{n}
\left(
y_j
-
f(\psib, t_j)
\right)^2
\end{split}
\end{equation}
$$ {#eq-nlm-one-ls}

with

$$
\begin{equation}
\begin{split}
\psib
=
\begin{bmatrix}
\phi_1 & \phi_2 & \phi_3
\end{bmatrix}
.
\end{split}
\end{equation}
$$ {#eq-param}


